In 2023, India's medical education regulator won something most MBBS students still don't understand the value of. The National Medical Commission received a 10-year recognition from the World Federation for Medical Education, meaning every one of India's 700-plus medical colleges is now listed in the World Directory of Medical Schools, the exact list international licensing bodies check before they'll even open your application. It didn't make practicing abroad automatic. It made it possible again.

## **What WFME recognition actually changed**

Starting in 2024, the ECFMG (the body that certifies foreign doctors to enter US residency) began requiring applicants to be graduates of a WFME-recognized medical school. Without NMC's recognition, every Indian MBBS graduate would have quietly lost eligibility for US residency, regardless of marks, regardless of USMLE scores. That door was closing. WFME recognition reopened it, for all of India's medical colleges at once, for ten years.

{% statCallout
   number="700+"
   label="Indian medical colleges now listed in the World Directory of Medical Schools under NMC's 10-year WFME recognition." /%}

This wasn't cosmetic. It's the difference between an ECFMG application getting read and getting auto-rejected before a human sees it.

## **What it didn't change**

WFME recognition is a quality stamp on your medical school. It is not a licensing exam, and it doesn't replace one. Whichever country you want to practice in still runs its own gate:

{% table %}
- **Destination**
- **You still need**
- **What WFME changed**
---
- **United States**
- USMLE Step 1, 2, 3
- Made ECFMG certification possible at all, post-2024
---
- **United Kingdom**
- PLAB 1 and 2
- Adds a quality-assurance layer; GMC already recognized Indian degrees separately
---
- **Australia / New Zealand**
- AMC exams
- Same pattern; the exam stays, the underlying degree now carries formal global standing
{% /table %}

The India-side reform that was supposed to make this cleaner, a single National Exit Test replacing both NEET-PG and FMGE, isn't happening soon. The NMC confirmed in 2026 that NExT is deferred by three to four years, with a trial run not expected before 2028 or 2029. NMC chairperson Dr Abhijat Sheth's stated reason was blunt: "We want to perfect the model before full rollout." Until then, NEET-PG remains the PG entrance exam, FMGE remains the exam foreign graduates take to practice in India, and none of that touches what you need for licensing abroad.

## **The global standard nobody's syllabus covers yet**

While regulators were sorting out recognition and licensing, a separate and genuinely global effort was underway: figuring out what a medical graduate should actually know about AI. A 2026 scoping review in npj Digital Medicine searched every major database back to inception, screened 2,877 studies, and pulled 54 that specifically proposed AI competencies for undergraduate medical education, across 22 countries.

What they found wasn't a single standard. It was fragmentation, 564 separate competency statements, nobody agreeing on a common list. The researchers synthesized all of it into one taxonomy: 7 domains, 37 competencies.

{% table %}
- **Domain**
- **What it covers**
---
- **AI ethics**
- Bias, consent, fairness in AI-assisted care
---
- **AI law and regulation**
- Liability, data protection, approval pathways
---
- **AI professionalism in healthcare**
- Disclosure to patients, appropriate reliance
---
- **Clinical applications of AI**
- Where it's actually deployed, diagnostics to triage
---
- **Critical appraisal of AI output**
- Reading a model's answer like evidence, not a verdict
---
- **Research and innovation in AI**
- How these tools get validated before they reach a ward
---
- **Theory and foundations of AI**
- Enough of the mechanics to know what's actually happening
{% /table %}

No accreditor anywhere has made this mandatory yet. But WFME's own standards are under active revision toward 2030, and a competency map this detailed, built from 22 countries' worth of proposals, tends to become policy faster than people expect.

{% callout type="tip" %}
This is the rare case where being early has almost no downside. Nobody's behind on a global AI-competency standard that doesn't formally exist yet. Everyone building this skill now is just ahead.
{% /callout %}

## **Why this matters even if you never leave India**

None of this is only relevant if you're planning to emigrate. WFME recognition, NExT's delay, and the AI-competency gap all point at the same thing: the credential your medical school gives you and the competence you actually walk in with are being evaluated by increasingly separate, increasingly global yardsticks. A degree gets you read. It doesn't get you hired, matched, or trusted with a patient.

{% actionBox %}
**Where to start**

- Confirm your own college's WDOMS listing directly at search.wdoms.org, don't assume; recognition is per-institution, not automatic for every campus a university runs.
- Pick your target country's exam early if you're planning to go abroad. USMLE, PLAB, and AMC have different timelines, different costs, and different clinical-experience requirements, and none of them wait for you to decide in your final year.
- Treat the 7 AI competency domains as a checklist, not a vague aspiration. Critical appraisal of AI output and clinical applications are the two most testable in an OSCE-style format right now.
- Don't confuse "I use ChatGPT to study" with AI competency. The taxonomy above is about judgment and regulation, not tool familiarity.
{% /actionBox %}

## **Frequently asked questions**

### **Is my MBBS degree valid abroad now that NMC has WFME recognition?**

Recognition means your college is listed in the World Directory of Medical Schools, which most countries' licensing bodies require before they'll even consider your application. It does not replace that country's licensing exam. You still need USMLE, PLAB, or the equivalent.

### **Do I still need to take USMLE or PLAB if my college is WFME accredited?**

Yes. WFME accreditation is about your medical school's quality standing, not a personal license to practice. Every destination country still requires its own exam regardless of where you studied.

### **Is NExT happening in 2026?**

No. NMC has confirmed it's deferred by three to four years, with a possible trial in 2028 or 2029. NEET-PG and FMGE continue in the meantime.

### **Do global medical education bodies require AI training now?**

Not formally, not yet. But a 2026 scoping review has already mapped a 7-domain, 37-competency taxonomy from research across 22 countries, and WFME's own standards are under revision toward 2030. This is very likely to become a formal expectation before most current students graduate.

## **The honest summary**

Your MBBS degree carries more weight abroad in 2026 than it did in 2022, because of a regulatory win most students never noticed. It still won't get you licensed anywhere on its own. NExT was supposed to modernize that path from the India side; it's been pushed to the end of the decade instead. Meanwhile, a new global expectation, AI competency, is being defined in research papers right now, before any accreditor has made it mandatory. Recognition opened a door. What you do before you walk through it is still entirely on you.

